{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3ac23097-fdbf-4335-9d8e-f59e1838c37d","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe project itself is fine — the slowness is inherent to how `dotnet build` works from the CLI vs Visual Studio:\n\n| Factor | Visual Studio | `dotnet build` CLI |\n|---|---|---|\n| MSBuild process | Long-lived, in-process | New process every invocation |\n| Node reuse | Enabled | Disabled (`/nodeReuse:false`) |\n| NuGet restore | Skipped when up-to-date | Checked every time |\n\nThe 2–4s overhead is .NET startup + MSBuild init + SDK resolution + restore check — not actual compilation.\n\n## Recommendations (in order of impact)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\nKeeps the build host alive and only rebuilds on file changes — eliminates startup entirely:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Skip restore on incremental builds\nAfter your first build or after changing packages, use:\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\nThis cuts the NuGet restore check (~500ms+) on every invocation.\n\n### 3. Enable the MSBuild Server (.NET 7+/8+)\nSet this environment variable to keep a long-lived MSBuild server process (similar to what VS does):\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nSubsequent builds reuse the warm server, avoiding JIT and initialization costs.\n\n### 4. Enable MSBuild node reuse\nBy default, `dotnet build` passes `/nodeReuse:false`. Override it:\n```bash\nexport MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0\ndotnet build /nodeReuse:true\n```\nThis keeps MSBuild worker nodes alive between builds for faster subsequent runs.\n\n### 5. Combine flags in a shell alias\nFor quick edit-build-test cycles, add to your shell profile:\n```bash\nalias db='dotnet build --no-restore /nodeReuse:true'\n```\n\n**Bottom line:** Start with `dotnet watch build` for the best inner-loop experience. For one-off builds, `--no-restore` + the MSBuild server give the biggest wins with minimal effort.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b471b5ba-5c87-4a37-af81-333f66269e2b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer is reporting that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses the MSBuild Server (a long-running MSBuild process) which avoids the startup cost of MSBuild on every build invocation. When you run `dotnet build` from the CLI, it starts a new MSBuild process each time, which involves:\n\n1. .NET runtime startup\n2. MSBuild engine initialization\n3. Project file evaluation/parsing\n4. SDK resolution\n5. NuGet restore check\n\n\n6. Target graph evaluation\n\nVisual Studio keeps MSBuild running in-process, so it skips all of this overhead. The main solution is to enable the MSBuild build server in .NET 8+ by setting `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or using the `-nodeReuse:true` flag, which keeps MSBuild running as a long-lived process similar to what Visual Studio does.\n\nBy default, `dotnet build` kills MSBuild worker nodes after each build, but you can preserve them between builds by setting `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0`. For the inner development loop, `dotnet watch` avoids startup overhead entirely by keeping the process running and only rebuilding on file changes. Graph-based builds with `dotnet build /graph` can also improve performance for multi-project solutions. Actually, I need to reconsider the environment variable behavior here. The `MSBuildDisableNodeReuse` flag when set to `1` disables reuse, but `dotnet build` explicitly passes `/nodeReuse:false` on the command line anyway, so the environment variable approach might not override that. In newer .NET versions, the behavior has shifted, so the most reliable optimizations are using `--no-restore` to skip the NuGet check on incremental builds and leveraging `dotnet watch` to keep the build process running continuously.\n\nBeyond those, there's the MSBuild Server available in .NET 7+ that can be enabled with an environment variable to keep the build infrastructure persistent, and the `dotnet build-server` command manages these long-running servers. Let me think through what practical recommendations would actually help.","outputTokens":1519,"requestId":"2809:2346F7:5E2D5B1:659E4FA:69FBE28D"},"id":"7ec783ca-1ebf-44c7-8d63-81367624c16f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:54:05.071Z","parentId":"ff61a32c-9db0-4a94-be1e-a5e761315705"}
